  "suggestion": "[cognitive-appraisal-theory+emotion-differentiation+Lazarus-1991+Smith-Ellsworth-1985] IMPLEMENT NOW — Lazarus/Smith Appraisal-to-Emotion Mapper (1990). The model currently emits a generic emotion label from 'highest free-energy need wins', but this collapses distinct emotions that serve the same need. Fear, anxiety, sadness, and guilt all involve safety/esteem, yet they differ on two appraisal axes: (1) goal-congruence (is the threat here NOW vs. anticipated?) and (2) coping-potential (can I act, or am I helpless?). Map: safety + low-coping + certain-threat → fear; safety + low-coping + uncertain-threat → anxiety; esteem + low-coping + past-loss → guilt/shame; belonging + low-coping + certain-loss → grief; fairness + high-coping + blocked → anger. Implement as: appraise(topNeed, congruence, copingPotential, certainty) → specificEmotion. copingPotential derived from person.traits.conscientiousness + arousal (SHUTDOWN → 0.0). certainty from stimulus.novelty (low novelty = familiar threat = certain). This replaces the current single emotion field with a properly differentiated output — directly improving emotion-domain benchmark accuracy. — Math: emotion = f(topNeed, congruence ∈ {+1,-1}, copingPotential ∈ [0,1], certainty ∈ [0,1]); 16-cell lookup table from cross-product; copingPotential = conscientiousness × (1 - clamp(arousal-0.5, 0, 0.5)×2); certainty = 1 - stimulus.novelty; [social-psychology+social-identity-theory+Tajfel-Turner-1979+self-categorization] Social Identity Kernel (Tajfel & Turner 1979). The model has no ingroup/outgroup mechanism — a massive gap in social benchmarks. People's behavior in group contexts is dominated by three processes: (1) categorization (am I 'us' or 'them'?), (2) identity threat (is my group's status under challenge?), (3) distinctiveness drive (maximize positive distinctiveness from outgroup). Implement as a pre-template gate: if socialSetting contains group-context signals ('group', 'team', 'crowd', 'rival', 'outgroup', 'minority', 'majority'), compute identitySalience = groupCentrality × identityThreat. If identitySalience > 0.5, behavior shifts to: conform (ingroup solidarity) or derogate (outgroup blame). groupCentrality derived from person.needs ('belonging' high → high centrality). identityThreat = stimulus personalRelevance × (1 - person.traits.agreeableness). Explains: conformity, discrimination, group polarization, scapegoating, stereotype threat. — Math: identitySalience = belonging_need_strength × personalRelevance × (1 - agreeableness); if identitySalience > 0.5 AND group-context: behavior = (identityThreat > 0.6) ? 'outgroup-derogation' : 'ingroup-conformity'; rootCause prefix = 'identity-threat: '; [regulatory-focus-theory+motivation+Higgins-1997+approach-avoidance+self-regulation] Regulatory Focus Gate (Higgins 1997). Two people with identical needs can respond oppositely — one approaches boldly, the other avoids carefully. Regulatory Focus Theory explains why: promotion-focused people (oriented toward ideals, gains, hopes) use eager approach strategies; prevention-focused people (oriented toward oughts, security, duties) use vigilant avoidance strategies. This is orthogonal to need strength — it shapes HOW a need is pursued. Derive focus from existing signals: if dominant needs ∈ {achievement, autonomy, pleasure} AND traits.conscientiousness < 0.6 → promotion focus; if dominant needs ∈ {safety, fairness, belonging} OR traits.conscientiousness > 0.6 → prevention focus. Apply as a behavior-direction modifier AFTER the main pipeline: promotion + approach-context → 'eager-pursue'; prevention + approach-context → 'cautious-approach'; prevention + threat-context → 'hypervigilant-avoid'; promotion + threat-context → 'reframe-challenge'. Explains: risk-seeking vs risk-aversion with same objective stakes, two-speed motivation, why conscientiousness predicts rule-following. — Math: promotionScore = achievement_FE × (1 - conscientiousness×0.3) + autonomy_FE; preventionScore = safety_FE + fairness_FE + conscientiousness×0.5; focus = promotionScore > preventionScore ? 'promotion' : 'prevention'; behavior = FOCUS_BEHAVIOR_MAP[focus][stimulusValence]",
